The powers conferred by Pt 54 are broad and extend as far as directing a trustee, executor or administrator “to do or abstain from doing any act” (UCPR 
r 54.3(3)(d)
). However, despite the literal breadth of those words, the power is confined to directions within the scope of the trust or the proper administration of the estate: Templeton v Leviathan Pty Ltd (1921) 30 CLR 34; [1922] VLR 90; 28 ALR 95;  BC2100001 . Consequently, the rules only confer a power to decide questions that arise in the course of administering the trust or estate. They do not permit directions requiring or authorising departure from the substantive obligations and entitlements relating to the trust or estate: Gonzales v Claridades (2003) 58 NSWLR 211; [2003] NSWCA 227;  BC200304834 at [30]  ff (court had no power to authorise or direct the executrix to pay estate funds to fund the defence costs of a beneficiary accused of the murder of the settlors); Westfield Qld No 1Pty Ltd v Lend Lease Real Estate Investments Ltd [2008] NSWSC 516;  BC200803975 at [38]  ff (directions limited to questions arising in the general administration and execution of a trust — no power to “terminate” or “wind up” the trust).
